ANTHRAX - NETHERLANDS (02): QUERY CONTAMINATED MEAT ex SLOVAKIA
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Sat 11 Oct 2014
Source: Outbreak News Today [edited]
http://outbreaknewstoday.com/netherlands-beef-taken-off-the-market-due-to-anthrax-risk-60109/


The Dutch Food and Consumer Product Safety Authority (NVWA) announced Friday [10 Oct 2014] directing [that] a beef shipment from Poland [be] taken off the market due to the potential risk of the bacterial disease [due to] _Bacillus anthracis_. The shipment consisted of Polish and Slovak carcass parts.

On [Wed 8 Oct 2014], it became known that 2 of the carcasses from a Slovak livestock tested positive for anthrax.

The NVWA details the situation (translated): The cattle were slaughtered on [19 Sep 2014] in Poland. [No abnormalities were detected during] inspections before and after slaughter. On 27 Sep 2014, more than a week after the slaughter of anthrax [anthrax was diagnosed] on the holding of origin of 2 Slovak cattle. The incubation period in the cow is 3 to 7 days. It is unlikely that an ox is already contagious during the incubation period, but that cannot be completely ruled out. The incubation period in humans is 1 to 7 days. Cattle are significantly more susceptible to anthrax than humans. Research indicates that a person must ingest [contaminated meat] to become ill.

Food safety officials say it is not clear whether the potentially tainted beef found its way to supermarkets; however, they say the risk to consumers is considered very small.

[Byline: Robert Herriman]

